Audio Signal Processor in Docker 🎶

This project provides a simple yet powerful Python script to load, manipulate, and visualize audio signals. It is containerized using Docker, which means you can run it on any system without worrying about installing Python, ffmpeg, or any other dependencies.

The script performs the following actions:

    Loads a .wav audio file.

    Generates and saves plots of the original signal's waveform and spectrogram.

    Applies a simple echo effect.

    Saves the manipulated audio to a new .wav file.

    Saves a waveform plot of the manipulated audio.

📂 Project Structure

The repository is organized as follows:

/
├── Dockerfile              # Instructions to build the Docker image
├── README.md               # This file
├── audio_processor.py      # The main Python script for audio processing
├── requirements.txt        # Python package dependencies
└── your_audio_file.wav     # Your input audio file (replace with your own)

🚀 Getting Started

Follow these instructions to build and run the project on your local machine.

Prerequisites

You only need one thing installed:

    Docker: Make sure the Docker engine is running on your system. You can download it from the official Docker website.

Step-by-Step Instructions

    Clone the Repository
    Clone this repository to your local machine.
    Bash

git clone <your-repository-url>
cd <repository-name>

Add Your Audio File
Place the audio file you want to process into the project's root directory. It must be named your_audio_file.wav, or you will need to update the filename inside audio_processor.py.

Build the Docker Image
Open your terminal in the project directory and run the following command. This will build the Docker image and tag it as audio-processor.
Bash

docker build -t audio-processor .

Run the Container
First, create a local directory named output. This is where the container will place the resulting files.
Bash

mkdir output

Now, run the container. The -v flag maps your local output directory to the /output directory inside the container, allowing the script to save files back to your machine.
Bash

    docker run --rm \
    -v "$(pwd)/output:/output" \
    audio-processor

    Check Your Results!
    Once the script finishes, your output directory will contain the processed audio and the generated plots:

        audio_with_echo.wav

        original_waveform.png

        original_spectrogram.png

        echo_waveform.png

🛠️ How to Customize

You can easily modify the script to apply different effects or process different files.

    Change the Input File: To use a different audio filename, open audio_processor.py and change the file_path variable on line 31:
    Python

# Before
file_path = 'your_audio_file.wav'

# After
file_path = 'my_new_song.wav'

Remember to copy the new file into the main directory and rebuild the Docker image.

Modify the Audio Effect: The echo effect is defined around line 49 in audio_processor.py. Feel free to change the parameters or replace it with your own logic entirely.
Python

# Change delay time or echo volume
delay_seconds = 0.5 # From 0.25
y_delayed[delay_samples:] = y[:-delay_samples] * 0.3 # Echo is at 30% volume

After making changes, you must rebuild the Docker image using the docker build command from Step 3.
